In the absence of special transport mechanisms (which is not proven, see further in the text), the vacuolar accumulation ratios (VAR) could be predicted from a derivation of the Hendelson–Hasselbach equation using the calculated log D values. Indeed, for a diacidic base, the log D is a function of the acidity constants (pK
a) and the partition coefficient (log P):\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$ \log {D_{\rm{calculated}}} = \log P - \log [1 + 10^{\wedge} ({\rm p} K_{\rm{a 1}} - {\rm pH}) + 10^{\wedge} ({\rm p} {K_{\rm a1}} + {\rm p} {K_{{\rm{a}}2}} -
{\rm pH})]. $$
\end{document}

Instead of the calculated log D values, the experimental log D values can also be exploited, and the VAR were calculated as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$ {\rm VAR} = 10^\wedge (\log {D_{7.4}} - \log DpH). $$
\end{document}
